<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Choir_stalls_and_organ">Choir stalls and organ</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Architecture_of_cathedrals_and_great_churches&amp;action=edit&amp;section=27" title="Edit section: Choir stalls and organ"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<p>The term "choir" is used in two distinct ways in relation to cathedrals. It firstly means the <a href="/wiki/Choir" title="Choir">choir</a> of "choristers", often men and boys, that sing at the services; in medieval cathedrals, and sometimes still, the boys from a special <a href="/wiki/Choir_school" class="mw-redirect" title="Choir school">choir school</a>. It is also the term used for that <a href="/wiki/Choir_(architecture)" title="Choir (architecture)">section of the church</a> where the choir sits and stands to sing in services. In a cathedral or large church, there may be fixed seating in this area, called <a href="/wiki/Choir_stalls" class="mw-redirect" title="Choir stalls">choir stalls</a> which also provided seating for the cathedral clergy and some congregation. The choir stalls are often richly carved and decorated. The bishop's throne or <i><a href="/wiki/Cathedra" title="Cathedra">cathedra</a></i> is often located in this space. The choir may be separated from the nave by a highly decorated screen of wood or stone.<sup id="cite_ref-36" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-36">&#91;36&#93;</a></sup> 
</p><p>The organ which provides music and accompanies the choir may be located on the screen, or may be in the gallery above the choir, or in a transept. Some churches have an organ loft at the west end of the church.  These are usually a later addition to medieval churches; large examples had <a href="/wiki/Portative_organ" title="Portative organ">portative organs</a>, often several.<sup id="cite_ref-37" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-37">&#91;37&#93;</a></sup> 
</p>
<ul class="gallery mw-gallery-packed">
		<li class="gallerybox" style="width: 248px">
			<div class="thumb" style="width: 246px;"><span typeof="mw:File"><a href="/wiki/File:Almudena_CruzYOrgano.jpg" class="mw-file-description" title="Organ in the Almudena Cathedral, Madrid, Spain"><img alt="Organ in the Almudena Cathedral, Madrid, Spain" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/44/Almudena_CruzYOrgano.jpg/369px-Almudena_CruzYOrgano.jpg" decoding="async" width="246" height="185" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/44/Almudena_CruzYOrgano.jpg/555px-Almudena_CruzYOrgano.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/44/Almudena_CruzYOrgano.jpg/739px-Almudena_CruzYOrgano.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2560" data-file-height="1920" /></a></span></div>
			<div class="gallerytext"><a href="/wiki/Organ_(music)" title="Organ (music)">Organ</a> in the <a href="/wiki/Almudena_Cathedral" title="Almudena Cathedral">Almudena Cathedral</a>, <a href="/wiki/Madrid" title="Madrid">Madrid</a>, Spain</div>
		</li>
		<li class="gallerybox" style="width: 310.66666666667px">
			<div class="thumb" style="width: 308.66666666667px;"><span typeof="mw:File"><a href="/wiki/File:Albi_Cathedral_Choir_Wikimedia_Commons.jpg" class="mw-file-description" title="The choirstalls, screen and lectern of Albi Cathedral, France"><img alt="The choirstalls, screen and lectern of Albi Cathedral, France" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1f/Albi_Cathedral_Choir_Wikimedia_Commons.jpg/463px-Albi_Cathedral_Choir_Wikimedia_Commons.jpg" decoding="async" width="309" height="185" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1f/Albi_Cathedral_Choir_Wikimedia_Commons.jpg/695px-Albi_Cathedral_Choir_Wikimedia_Commons.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1f/Albi_Cathedral_Choir_Wikimedia_Commons.jpg/926px-Albi_Cathedral_Choir_Wikimedia_Commons.jpg 2x" data-file-width="4470" data-file-height="2676" /></a></span></div>
			<div class="gallerytext">The <a href="/wiki/Choir_(architecture)" title="Choir (architecture)">choirstalls</a>, screen and <a href="/wiki/Lectern" title="Lectern">lectern</a> of <a href="/wiki/Albi_Cathedral" title="Albi Cathedral">Albi Cathedral</a>, France</div>
		</li>
		<li class="gallerybox" style="width: 248px">
			<div class="thumb" style="width: 246px;"><span typeof="mw:File"><a href="/wiki/File:2004_norwich_cathedral_07.JPG" class="mw-file-description" title="A choir practising in Norwich Cathedral, England"><img alt="A choir practising in Norwich Cathedral, England" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1b/2004_norwich_cathedral_07.JPG/369px-2004_norwich_cathedral_07.JPG" decoding="async" width="246" height="185" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1b/2004_norwich_cathedral_07.JPG/555px-2004_norwich_cathedral_07.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1b/2004_norwich_cathedral_07.JPG/739px-2004_norwich_cathedral_07.JPG 2x" data-file-width="2848" data-file-height="2136" /></a></span></div>
			<div class="gallerytext">A choir practising in <a href="/wiki/Norwich_Cathedral" title="Norwich Cathedral">Norwich Cathedral</a>, <a href="/wiki/England" title="England">England</a></div>
		</li>
</ul>
<h4><span id="Font.2C_lectern_and_pulpit"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="Font,_lectern_and_pulpit">Font, lectern and pulpit</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Architecture_of_cathedrals_and_great_churches&amp;action=edit&amp;section=28" title="Edit section: Font, lectern and pulpit"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<p>Towards the western end of the nave stands the font, or water basin at which the rite of <a href="/wiki/Baptism" title="Baptism">Baptism</a> is performed. It is placed towards the door because the Baptism signifies entry into the community of the church. Standing to the front of the nave is a lectern from which the <a href="/wiki/Holy_Scripture" class="mw-redirect" title="Holy Scripture">Holy Scripture</a> is read. In many churches this takes the <a href="/wiki/Eagle_lectern" title="Eagle lectern">form of an eagle</a> which supports the book on its outstretched wings and is the symbol of <a href="/wiki/John_the_Evangelist" title="John the Evangelist">John the Evangelist</a>.
</p><p>The third significant furnishing of the nave is the pulpit or rostrum from which the <a href="/wiki/Sermon" title="Sermon">sermon</a> is preached and the biblical readings are expounded. The <a href="/wiki/Pulpit" title="Pulpit">pulpit</a> might be of marble or wood, and may be a simple structure or represent a highly elaborate carved sermon. It is often decorated with the winged figures of a man, a lion, a bull and an eagle, representing the <a href="/wiki/Gospel" title="Gospel">Gospel</a> writers, Matthew, Mark, Luke and John.<sup id="cite_ref-38" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-38">&#91;38&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<ul class="gallery mw-gallery-packed">
		<li class="gallerybox" style="width: 166.66666666667px">
			<div class="thumb" style="width: 164.66666666667px;"><span typeof="mw:File"><a href="/wiki/File:Salamanca_-_Catedral_Nueva,_Capilla_de_San_Lorenzo_5.JPG" class="mw-file-description" title="Font at Salamanca Cathedral, Spain"><img alt="Font at Salamanca Cathedral, Spain" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/dd/Salamanca_-_Catedral_Nueva%2C_Capilla_de_San_Lorenzo_5.JPG/247px-Salamanca_-_Catedral_Nueva%2C_Capilla_de_San_Lorenzo_5.JPG" decoding="async" width="165" height="220" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/dd/Salamanca_-_Catedral_Nueva%2C_Capilla_de_San_Lorenzo_5.JPG/371px-Salamanca_-_Catedral_Nueva%2C_Capilla_de_San_Lorenzo_5.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/dd/Salamanca_-_Catedral_Nueva%2C_Capilla_de_San_Lorenzo_5.JPG/495px-Salamanca_-_Catedral_Nueva%2C_Capilla_de_San_Lorenzo_5.JPG 2x" data-file-width="960" data-file-height="1280" /></a></span></div>
			<div class="gallerytext">Font at <a href="/wiki/Salamanca_Cathedral" class="mw-redirect" title="Salamanca Cathedral">Salamanca Cathedral</a>, Spain</div>
		</li>
		<li class="gallerybox" style="width: 166.66666666667px">
			<div class="thumb" style="width: 164.66666666667px;"><span typeof="mw:File"><a href="/wiki/File:Beverley_minster_028.JPG" class="mw-file-description" title="Lectern at Beverley Minster, England"><img alt="Lectern at Beverley Minster, England" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7f/Beverley_minster_028.JPG/247px-Beverley_minster_028.JPG" decoding="async" width="165" height="220" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7f/Beverley_minster_028.JPG/371px-Beverley_minster_028.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7f/Beverley_minster_028.JPG/495px-Beverley_minster_028.JPG 2x" data-file-width="1200" data-file-height="1600" /></a></span></div>
